  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How can I download computer science engineering books free?",
  "response": "Accessing high-quality computer science engineering books for free is possible through a variety of legal and reputable sources. Here are several options you can explore:\n\n1. **Open Educational Resources (OER):**\n   - **[OpenStax](https://openstax.org/):** Offers free, peer-reviewed textbooks for various subjects, including some computer science topics.\n   - **[Saylor Academy](https://www.saylor.org/books/):** Provides free textbooks for courses in computer science and engineering.\n\n2. **University Open Courseware:**\n   - **[MIT OpenCourseWare](https://ocw.mit.edu/index.htm):** Access lecture notes, assignments, and sometimes free textbooks used in MIT's computer science courses.\n   - **[Carnegie Mellon Open Learning Initiative](https://oli.cmu.edu/):** Offers free course materials in computer science.\n\n3. **Free eBook Platforms:**\n   - **[Project Gutenberg](https://www.gutenberg.org/):** While primarily focused on literature, it has some technical books in the public domain.\n   - **[Internet Archive](https://archive.org/):** Hosts a vast collection of books, including those on computer science and engineering. Ensure you check the licensing for each book to confirm it's free to download legally.\n\n4. **Author and Publisher Websites:**\n   - Some authors release their textbooks for free on their personal or university web pages. For example, **\"Structure and Interpretation of Computer Programs\"** by Harold Abelson and Gerald Jay Sussman is available for free online.\n   - **[GitHub](https://github.com/):** Many authors and educators share their textbooks and resources here. Searching for specific titles or topics can yield free materials.\n\n5. **Public Libraries and Institutional Access:**\n   - **[Your local library:** Many public libraries offer free access to eBooks and academic resources. Platforms like **OverDrive** or **Libby** are commonly used by libraries to lend digital books.\n   - **University Libraries:** If you're affiliated with an educational institution, take advantage of their digital library resources, which often include a wide range of engineering and computer science books.\n\n6. **Free Online Courses with Materials:**\n   - **[Coursera](https://www.coursera.org/), [edX](https://www.edx.org/), and [Udacity](https://www.udacity.com/):** These platforms offer free courses in computer science that may include downloadable reading materials and recommended textbooks.\n\n7. **Specialized Platforms:**\n   - **[FreeTechBooks](http://www.freetechbooks.com/):** A directory of free computer science, engineering, and programming books, textbooks, and lecture notes.\n   - **[BookBoon](https://bookboon.com/):** Offers free textbooks for students and professionals in various fields, including engineering and IT.\n\n**Tips for Accessing Free Resources:**\n\n- **Verify Licensing:** Always ensure that the books are legally free to download. Look for Creative Commons licenses or public domain status.\n- **Check for Open Access Editions:** Some textbooks have free editions available, especially older versions that are still valuable for foundational knowledge.\n- **Utilize Academic Networks:** Platforms like **ResearchGate** or **Academia.edu** sometimes have authors sharing their publications for free.\n\nBy leveraging these resources, you can access a wealth of computer science engineering knowledge without infringing on copyright laws. Always prioritize legal avenues to support authors and publishers who create valuable educational content.",
